them the nature of soul and intellect, theories of how seeing takes place, issues in ethics, and the nature of fate. The text is based upon a new collation of the principal manuscript, the ninth century Venetus Marcianus graecus 258, and the apparatus corrects Bruns' misreportings of the principal manuscript and of the others that he used. Account has also been taken of the medieval Arabic and Latin versions of some of the sections which circulated independently, notably On Intellect which had a substantial influence on medieval philosophy. The introduction is chiefly concerned with the manuscripts and the relation between them. The commentary is based on the notes to the editor's English translation of the work (London: Duckworth and Ithaca: Cornell University Press, 2004); however, the commentary also takes into account more recent work on the collection by various scholars.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Greek, Ancient (to 1453).0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aClassical and Ancient Near Eastern StudiesxClassical StudiesxAncient Philosophy. 0aClassical and Ancient Near Eastern StudiesxClassical StudiesxGreekxGreek Authors. 0aPhilosophyxHistory of PhilosophyxAncient Philosophy. 4aAlexander von Aphrodisias. 4aAristotelismus. 4aPhilosophie. 4aSeele. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAlexander of Aphrodisias.  aAristotelianism.  aPhilosophy.  aSoul.1 aSharples, Robert W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN0 cprintz978311019644340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311097899540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110978995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110978995/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_C